  footnotes: []
english:
  title: An Edict for Jayou, Head Seat of the Yogacara School, Upon His Appointment as Ecclesiastical Commissioner
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: I address this to Jayou. Names and forms are the means by which the Way is illuminated, yet they are not the Way itself. And yet without names and forms, one cannot enter the supreme Way. Therefore, even the great bodhisattvas have borrowed words to transmit the dharma across countless ages, making manifest what was hidden and bright what was obscure. So if one wishes to enter the path of the sage while refusing to travel through names and forms—such a one has never existed. Here now is an elder of the Yogacara school who has truly embodied this Way and earned the reverence of the scholars of our time. Should we not then bestow upon him marks of esteem and grant him special favor? When those of virtue are advanced, all people recognize the encouragement. This is the natural order of things.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yogacara (유가종/瑜伽宗): One of the major schools of Mahayana Buddhism, emphasizing the role of consciousness in constructing reality.'
  - key: ''
    value: This edict follows the classical Chinese didactic style, using Buddhist philosophical principles to justify an administrative appointment and honor.
